The '''UCL Centre for the History of Medicine''' (formerly the '''Wellcome Trust Centre for the History of Medicine''') is an academic research and teaching centre for the [[history of medicine]] located in [[London]], [[United Kingdom]] and a part of [[University College London]] (UCL). The Centre was founded in 1966 and received its primary funding from the [[Wellcome Trust]] until 2012.<ref>http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?sectioncode=26&storycode=411309 Terminal diagnosis for UCL’s history of medicine centre</ref> As of September 2012, it had four emeritus academic staff, six teaching staff, and associated staff in a number of other UCL departments.<ref name=people>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/histmed/people|title=People|publisher=UCL Centre for the History of Medicine|accessdate=27 September 2012}}</ref>

The Centre is based in the UCL Medical Sciences Building in the main UCL campus on Gower Street in the [[Bloomsbury]] area of [[Central London]], close to the [[British Library]] and [[University College Hospital]].<ref name=history>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/histmed/about/location|title=Location|publisher=Wellcome Trust Centre for the History of Medicine|accessdate=2 November 2010}}</ref>

==History==

The Wellcome Trust funded the establishment of a History of Medicine department at UCL in 1966, headed by Edwin Clarke.<ref name=the20apr2010>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=411309| title=Terminal diagnosis for UCL’s history of medicine centre|accessdate=2 November 2010|publisher=Times Higher Education|date=20 April 2010}}</ref> In 1993 the Centre started running a series of witness seminars to record medicine's key events.<ref name=history/><ref name=witness>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storyCode=159666&sectioncode=26| title=A historical postmortem|accessdate=2 November 2010|publisher=Times Higher Education| date=11 May 2001}}</ref> In February 2010 the centre was the first history unit in the world to be nominated for centre collaborative status with the [[World Health Organization]].<ref name=history/><ref name=telegraphpemberton>{{cite news|url=http://www.telegraph.co.uk/health/healthadvice/maxpemberton/7726261/The-Wellcome-Trust-Centre-for-the-History-of-Medicine-must-be-saved-from-closure.html| title=The Wellcome Trust Centre for the History of Medicine must be saved from closure|accessdate=2 November 2010|publisher=The Telegraph|date=17 May 2010}}</ref> In April 2010 it was announced that the Wellcome Trust would not be renewing its grant for the Centre, and that it would therefore be closing within two years.<ref name=history/><ref name=the20apr2010/><ref name=telegraphpemberton/><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.timeshighereducation.co.uk/story.asp?storycode=411405| title=Double jeopardy: UCL and charity's clashes contributed to centre's fall|accessdate=2 November 2010|publisher=Times Higher Education| date=29 April 2010}}</ref>

On 15 March 2011 it was announced that the Centre would be relaunched as the UCL Centre for the History of Medicine for the 2011/2012 academic year.<ref name=marchannounce>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/histmed/library/new_centre|title=The new UCL Centre for the History of Medicine - Director's Announcement|accessdate=28 May 2011|publisher=UCL Centre for the History of Medicine}}</ref> It was announced that the Centre would move from the Wellcome Building on [[Euston Road]] to UCL's Medical Sciences Building on Gower Street and that its research focus would now be the history of neurosciences and related fields.<ref name=history/><ref name=marchannounce/>

==Publications==

During its history the Centre has sponsored a number of publications:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ucl.ac.uk/histmed/publications|title=Publications|publisher=UCL Centre for the History of Medicine|accessdate=28 May 2011}}</ref>

*''Clio Medica'', a series of research monographs on  the history of medicine and health care; published cooperatively with the  Dutch publisher [[Rodopi]].
*''Sir Henry Wellcome Asian Series'', a series of texts and translations of [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[Chinese language|Chinese]], and [[Sanskrit]] medical classics, and research works related to them; published by [[Brill Publishers|Brill]].
*''Medical History'', a refereed research journal, available as an [[open access journal]].
*''Wellcome Witnesses to Twentieth Century Medicine'', transcripts of seminars at which significant figures in 20th-century medicine  discuss specific discoveries or events in recent medical history
*''New Perspectives in South Asian History'', a series of books on social and economic topics relating to public health and economic development.

